{{US-historian-stub}}

A '''political midlife crisis''' is a turning point or watershed moment in the fortunes of a governance entity such as an empire, nation, faction, political party, or international alliance. The concept was first advanced by Arab thinker [[Ibn Khaldun]] (1332–1406), who compared an individual's decline after reaching the age of forty, with the sedentary decline that occurs in a dynasty.<ref>[[Ibn Khaldun]], ''[[Muqaddimah]]'', Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1978, p. 285.</ref> More recently, political scientist [[Joshua S Goldstein]] has used the concept in his 1988 book, ''Long Cycles: Prosperity and War in the Modern Age''.
A political midlife crisis occurs following a prolonged [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of optimism, economic progress, conquest, or other success, and typically features attacks on, or threats toward, a rival power. The attacks are vigorously opposed, ending in stalemate or defeat.
The term "political midlife crisis" adverts to the concept of "[[midlife crisis]]", which describes a supposed crisis in a middle-aged person's identity and self-confidence, caused by events that highlight the person's aging, mortality, and any perceived deficiencies in life attainments. The concept of political midlife crisis applies the concept of midlife crisis to the concepts of "[[social organism]]" and "[[body politic]]", which view an entire human [[society]] as a kind of single super-organism.
==History of the concept== [[Ibn Khaldun]], in the ''[[Muqaddimah]]'' (1377), set out a general theory of the rise and fall of regimes. A ruthless conqueror with a "[[desert]] attitude" establishes a new dynasty. Over some years, royal authority and ''asabiyyah'' ([[social cohesion]]) enable "expansion to the limit". Then, as in the life of an individual, a turning point is reached. According to Ibn Khaldun, when a man reaches forty he naturally stops growing, then begins to decline. The same is the case with a sedentary civilization's culture.<ref>[[Ibn Khaldun]], ''[[Muqaddimah]]'', Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1978, p. 285.</ref> The dynasty's new sedentary culture fosters a love of luxury and pomp. The people become over-taxed and acquire a "habit of subservience".<ref>[[Ibn Khaldun]], ''[[Muqaddimah]]'', Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1978, p. 248.</ref> Their rulers subvert property rights and become weak, dishonest, and divided. Finally, after three generations—equivalent to a human lifespan—the dynasty becomes "senile and coercive".<ref>[[Ibn Khaldun]], ''[[Muqaddimah]]'', Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1978, pp. 245, 255.</ref> There may follow a final "brightly burning show of power",<ref>[[Ibn Khaldun]], ''[[Muqaddimah]]'', Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1978, p. 246.</ref> but collapse of the dynasty is inevitable. A new dynasty takes over, and the cycle continues. Ibn Khaldun says: "This senility is a chronic disease that cannot be cured, because it is something natural."<ref>[[Ibn Khaldun]], ''[[Muqaddimah]]'', Routledge and Kegan Paul, 1978, p. 245.</ref>
In 1988 [[Joshua S Goldstein]] advanced the concept of the political midlife crisis in his book on "[[Long Cycle Theory|long cycle theory]]", ''Long Cycles: Prosperity and War in the Modern Age'',<ref name=goldstein>{{citation |first=Joshua |last= Goldstein |authorlink=Joshua S Goldstein |title=Long Cycles: Prosperity and War in the Modern Age |url=http://www.joshuagoldstein.com/jgcycle.htm |publisher= Yale University Press |year=1988}}</ref>{{pn|date=October 2017}} which offers four examples of the process:
*The [[British Empire]] and the [[Crimean War]] (1853–1856): A century after Britain's successful launch of the [[Industrial Revolution]], and following the subsequent British railway boom of 1815–1853, Britain, in the [[Crimean War]], attacked the [[Russian Empire]], which was perceived as a threat to [[Company rule in India|British India]] and to eastern Mediterranean trade routes to India. The Crimean War highlighted the poor state of the [[British Army]], and Britain took no further part in European wars until the outbreak of [[World War I]] in 1914. *The [[German Empire]] (Second Reich) and [[World War I]] (1914–1918): Under Chancellor [[Otto von Bismarck]], Germany had been unified between 1864 and 1871, and then had seen 40 years' rapid industrial, military, and colonial expansion. In 1914 the [[Schlieffen Plan]] for conquering [[French Third Republic|France]] in eight weeks was to have been followed by the subjugation of the [[Russian Empire]], leaving Germany the master of ''[[Mitteleuropa]]'' ([[Central Europe]]). In the event, France, [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|Britain]], Russia, and the [[United States]] fought Germany to a standstill, to defeat, and to a humiliating peace settlement at [[Versailles Treaty|Versailles]] (1919) and the establishment of Germany's unstable [[Weimar Republic]] (1919–33), in a prelude to [[World War II]]. *The [[Soviet Union]] and the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] (1962): The Soviet Union had industrialised rapidly under [[Joseph Stalin]] and, following World War II, had become a rival nuclear [[superpower]] to the [[United States]]. In 1962 Soviet Premier [[Nikita Khrushchev]], intent on securing strategic parity with the United States, covertly, with the support of [[Fidel Castro]], shipped nuclear missiles to Castro's [[Cuba under Fidel Castro|Cuba]], 70 miles from the US state of [[Florida]]. US President [[John F. Kennedy]] blockaded ("quarantined") the island of Cuba and negotiated the Soviet missiles' removal from Cuba (in exchange for the subsequent removal of US missiles from Turkey).{{vague|date=December 2017}} *The [[United States]] and the [[Vietnam War]] (1955–1975): During World War II and the ensuing postwar period, the United States had greatly expanded its military capacities and [[military-industrial complex|industries]]. After France, supported financially by the US, had been defeated in Vietnam in 1954 and that country had been temporarily split into [[North Vietnam|North]] and [[South Vietnam]] under the 1954 [[1954 Geneva Conference|Geneva Accords]]; and when war had broken out between the North and South following South Vietnam President [[Ngo Dinh Diem]]'s refusal to permit all-Vietnam elections in 1956 as stipulated in the Geneva Accords, the ideologically [[Anti-communism|anti-communist]] United States supported South Vietnam with materiel in a [[Cold War]] [[proxy war]] and by degrees allowed itself to be drawn into South Vietnam's losing struggle against communist North Vietnam and the [[Viet Cong]] acting in South Vietnam. Ultimately, following the defeat of South Vietnam and the United States, the US's governing belief that South Vietnam's defeat would result in all of remaining [[Indochina]] "going communist" (as proclaimed by the US's "[[domino theory]]"), proved erroneous.<ref name=goldstein/>{{pn|date=October 2017}}
Following [[Al Qaeda]]'s [[September 11 attacks| attacks on the United States on September 11, 2001]], and the United States' subsequent inconclusive wars in [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|Afghanistan (2001–present)]] and [[Iraq War|Iraq (2003–2011)]], initiated by US President [[George W. Bush]], Professor [[Gary Weaver]] and his co-author [[Adam Mendelson]], writing in 2008, cited a survey of 109 historians, 99% of whom rated Bush a "failure" as president, two-thirds rating him the "worst ever". Weaver and Mendelson wrote that the United States had been in its "childhood" before 1898; in its "adolescence", 1898–1945; in "young adulthood", 1945–1991; in "adulthood", 1991–2001. Weaver and Mendelson, from their 2008 perspective, anticipated that the traumas of the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|George W. Bush presidency]] would "season [the Unitied States] with new strength, wisdom and maturity", enabling it to move forward from this political midlife crisis.<ref>Gary Weaver and [[Adam Mendelson]], ''America's Midlife Crisis'', Intercultural Press, 2008.</ref>{{pn|date=December 2017}}
The [[European debt crisis]] (2009–present) has been called the [[European Union]]'s midlife crisis in articles by [[Gideon Rachman]],<ref>{{citation |first=Gideon |last=Rachman |authorlink=Gideon Rachman |title=Europe Is Having a Midlife Crisis |url=https://www.ft.com/content/4d277112-7d68-11df-a0f5-00144feabdc0 |work=[[Financial Times]] |date=21 July 2010}} {{subscription required|date=December 2017}}</ref> [[Roland Benedikter]],<ref>{{citation |first=Roland |last=Benedikter |title=Europe's Midlife Crisis |url=http://en.interaffairs.ru/events/524-europes-midlife-crisis-what-the-continent-needs-to-do-now.html |work=[[International affairs (disambiguation)|interaffairs.ru]] |date=20 May 2014}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=October 2017}} and [[Natalie Nougayrede]].<ref>{{citation |first=Natalie |last=Nougayrede |title=Europe in crisis? Despite everything, its citizens have never had it so good |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2017/apr/01/european-citizens-have-never-had-it-so-good |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=1 April 2017}}</ref> Arguably [[Brexit]] and the ongoing migrant crisis are further symptoms of an ongoing European midlife crisis.{{original research?|date=June 2018}}
==Other examples== {{Expand section|date=December 2017}} [[Leo Tolstoy]], in ''[[War and Peace]]'', asks about the [[French invasion of Russia|1812 French invasion of Russia]]: "What is the cause of this movement which took the French army all the way from Paris to Moscow, and then back to Paris? A system, a mysterious callous force&nbsp;... the unconscious swarm-life of mankind." The [[France|French]] decision to invade [[Russia]] in 1812 had been intended to secure a Franco-Russian alliance that would then conquer [[India]], but it ended in a rout and in the exile of [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Bonaparte]]—prompting Stanley Michalak to write that "In 1812 Napoleon failed the supreme test of [[power politics]]—knowing when to stop."<ref>Stanley Michalak, ''A Primer in Power Politics'', SR Books, 2001, p. 6.</ref>{{better source example|date=December 2017}}
The 1919 [[Amritsar massacre]] in [[India]], a turning point for that country's [[British Raj]], horrified world opinion and encouraged agitation for Indian independence.<ref>{{citation |first=William |last=Dalrymple |authorlink=William Dalrymple (historian) |title=Apologising for Amritsar Is Pointless |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/feb/23/apologising-amritsar-teach-british-empire |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=23 February 2013}}</ref> Similarly, the 1960 [[Sharpeville massacre]] in [[Apartheid]] [[South Africa]] brought on a state of emergency and drove the [[African National Congress]] underground and into armed struggle.<ref>[overcomingapartheid.msu.edu;]</ref><ref>[[Michelle Miller]], "Sharpeville Massacre Marked Turning Point in SA History", [cbsnews.com], 18 December 2013.</ref>
[[Egypt]]'s defeat in the 1967 [[Six-Day War]] with [[Israel]] was a political turning point for Egypt's President [[Gamal Abdel Nasser]] and for the Arab cause. Nasser immediately offered his resignation and died three years later; the cause of [[Arab nationalism]] never recovered.<ref>Anonymous, "Six-day War Marked Political Turning Point in the Arab World", 2 June 2017.</ref> Mark Katz<ref> Mark Katz, ''Revolutions and Revolutionary Waves'', St Martin's Press, 1997, p 83</ref> describes the event as a "crisis of confidence from which [Egypt] never recovered".
An ''[[The Economist|Economist]]'' article was one of the first to recognize the nature of the 2007–08 [[credit crunch]].<ref>{{citation |title=The Turning Point |work=[[The Economist]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224130945/http://www.economist.com/node/9831159 |archivedate= 2014-12-24 |url=http://www.economist.com/node/9831159 |date=20 September 2017}}</ref> Farkas Beata sees the [[Euro crisis]] as another financial turning point. <ref>Farkas Beata, "The Crisis as a Turning Point in the European Convergence Model", in Farkas Beata, ''The Aftermath of the Crisis in the European Union’', Cambridge Scholars Publishing, 2013, pp. 134–151.</ref>
==Nations at risk== ''[[The Economist]]'' says it is a "question of when, not if, real trouble will hit [[China]]".<ref>Economist, "The Coming Debt Bust", ''[[The Economist]]'', 7/5/2016.</ref> The country is approaching the limits of its potential power and growth, having in 2010 reached the [[Lewis turning point]], an indicator of labour shortages.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dammon Loyalka |first=Michelle |title=Chinese Labor, Cheap No More |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/18/opinion/chinese-labor-cheap-no-more.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=16 January 2015 }}</ref>
